# Web Development Patterns for Educational Content

## HTML Structure Standards
- Always use proper DOCTYPE declaration: `<!DOCTYPE html>`
- Include semantic HTML5 elements when appropriate (header, nav, main, section, article, footer)
- Use descriptive alt attributes for images
- Follow accessibility best practices with proper heading hierarchy (h1-h6)
- Include viewport meta tag for responsive design: `<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">`

## CSS Organization
- Use external CSS files when possible (style.css)
- Follow BEM methodology for class naming when teaching advanced concepts
- Use CSS custom properties (variables) for consistent theming
- Implement responsive design with media queries
- Use flexbox and grid for modern layouts

## JavaScript Best Practices
- Use `const` and `let` instead of `var` (ES6+ standards)
- Implement proper error handling with try-catch blocks
- Use template literals for string interpolation
- Follow functional programming principles when appropriate
- Use modern array methods (map, filter, reduce) instead of traditional loops

## Educational Code Examples
- Keep examples simple and focused on single concepts
- Include comments explaining complex logic
- Use descriptive variable and function names
- Provide both basic and advanced implementations
- Include console.log statements for debugging demonstrations

## File Organization in Sessions
- **index.html** - Main HTML structure
- **script.js** - JavaScript functionality
- **style.css** - CSS styling
- **settings-template.json** - Configuration files
- **Session X.md** - Session documentation

